            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Priya Sharma was raised in the neat suburbs of Fremont, the daughter of Indian immigrants who equated success with engineering and medicine. Her childhood was a blend of academic pressure and quiet rebellion, where she would lose herself in art history books instead of calculus problems. A high school field trip to the de Young Museum became her turning point; standing before a vibrant Rothko, she felt a sense of purpose her parents\u2019 ambitions could never provide. Bucking expectations, she enrolled in SF State\u2019s Arts Administration program.\n\nHer career began with an unpaid internship at a small gallery in the Mission, where she learned to do everything from patching drywall to writing press releases. Priya\u2019s tenacity and sharp eye for compelling programming saw her rise steadily. She moved from a coordinator at a theatre company to a manager at Yerba Buena Center for the Arts, finally landing her current role as Director of Programming for a major cultural foundation. She now orchestrates a complex calendar of art exhibitions, public performances, and culinary events, finding deep satisfaction in making culture accessible.\n\nAt 44, Priya\u2019s life is a curated balance. Her mornings begin with strong coffee and a peruse of arts journals before she catches the N-Judah from her cozy Cole Valley apartment. The 4.5-mile commute is a cherished ritual\u2014a time to observe the city\u2019s rhythm or listen to a podcast. A decade-long relationship ended in her late thirties when her partner, a tech executive, couldn\u2019t grasp why she\u2019d work late for an artist\u2019s installation instead of a lucrative product launch. The split was painful but clarifying, cementing her identity as someone whose life\u2019s work was her life\u2019s passion.\n\nHer social circle is a tight-knit group of fellow curators, artists, and chefs. Evenings are often spent at gallery openings or testing a new restaurant menu for a future event collaboration. Her dream isn\u2019t about climbing higher but broadening her impact; she\u2019s currently developing a proposal for a city-wide arts festival for public school students. For Priya, San Francisco is not just a home; it is the canvas, the medium, and the audience for the life she so deliberately designed for herself."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was 18, riding the N-Judah outbound after a tense weekend at home in Fremont. The arguments about her \"useless\" Art History major were still ringing in her ears. As the train dipped into the Sunset Tunnel, the city lights vanished, and she felt a sudden, profound sense of relief. When it emerged into the cool Cole Valley air, she wasn\u2019t going to a dorm; she was going home. That short, dark passage became a baptism, washing away the suburbs and cementing her new identity in the city.\n\n2.\nAt 22, it was 1 AM in the unheated Mission gallery. Her hands ached, covered in drywall dust and white paint. The gallerist had left her to patch a hole before a new show installed the next day. She was exhausted, unpaid, and running on cheap coffee. But as she smoothed the final layer of spackle, a wave of fierce satisfaction washed over her. This was real. She wasn't just studying art; she was building the walls that would hold it. It was the moment she knew she belonged.\n\n3.\nShe remembers the exact moment it ended, at age 38. He stood by the door of their apartment, keys in hand, exasperated. \"It\u2019s just a sculpture, Priya. I have a billion-dollar launch tomorrow.\" She was about to leave for YBCA to help an artist adjust the lighting on a massive, delicate installation. In his words, she didn't hear a complaint, but a chasm. The heartbreak was sharp, but beneath it was a bedrock of certainty. She chose the sculpture. She chose herself. She never regretted it.\n\n4.\nIt wasn't a glamorous opening night, but a free family day at Yerba Buena she had programmed. From a distance, she watched a young girl, no older than ten, utterly mesmerized by a strange, kinetic sound installation. The girl\u2019s father was trying to explain it, but she just stood there, listening with her whole body. In that child's quiet awe, Priya saw the entire purpose of her work. It wasn't about the elites or the critics; it was about opening a door for that one kid. The seed for her student festival was planted.\n\n5.\nJust last month, on a foggy Tuesday. She was crowded around a small table in a new Hayes Valley spot with her circle: a chef, a painter, and a fellow curator. They weren't networking; they were passionately debating the merits of a new film while sharing plates. The conversation flowed from public art funding to the perfect spice blend. Looking at their faces, animated in the candlelight, Priya felt a quiet, profound sense of rightness. This\u2014this vibrant, intelligent, passionate chosen family\u2014was the life she had so carefully, deliberately built for herself."
